How to work with Services in a Ubuntu System:
---------------------------------------------

=> List all currently running services: This command filters the list to show only services in the 'running' sub-state:

  #systemctl list-units --type=service --state=running

=> List all active services: This includes services that are running or have exited but are still considered 'active' by systemd:

  #systemctl list-units --type=service --state=active

=> Check the status of a specific service: Replace service_name (e.g., ssh, apache2) with the actual name of the service you want to check:

  # systemctl status service_name

=> Reload a service's configuration (without full restart):

  # sudo systemctl reload <service_name>


**** Warning: There is no single command to restart all services at once without causing potential issues. Attempting to do so via scripts or complex systemctl commands 
may lead to system instability, especially as services have complex interdependencies (e.g., networking services stopping before other services have finished their graceful shutdown). 
A full system reboot remains the safest approach for a complete service refresh.
